Plotting Challenges #1

Flow cytometry plots

30 March 2021

Data

This experiment is analysing the CD4+ and CD8+ T cells from mouse tumours, including the phenotype of the CD8+ T cells. The test groups are: Control 9 samples, Drug 1 9 samples, Drug 2 9 samples. The starting data is the Excel file flow_output.xlsx, sheet called Raw flow output. Many thanks to Emily Lelliott, Oliaro Lab for kindly providing the data.

Download flow_output.xlsx

Aim

Create a script to make a reproducible plot that looks similar to plot 1A, 1B or 2 below. Through taking part in this challenge you will be learn how to use R to import Excel files, wrangle data and create and customise plots.

Prerequisties

Basic familiarity with R and ggplot. This could be obtained from reading this Introduction to R for Biologists material.

Steps

Plot 1A - Beginner

Packages to read in the data and analyse it will be loaded. Excel data will be imported and wrangled for appropriate reading with ggplot. Finally a panel of dot plots like Plot 1A will be generated.

  1. Load any packages needed.
  2. Import the data from the Excel file.
  3. Remove the rows not needed for the plot (in column Sample:, rows containing Mean and SD).
  4. Format the data to plot with ggplot.
  5. Create one plot for each cell type (plot 1A).

Plot 1B - Intermediate

In addition to the steps above, the plot will be customised. A line will be added through the median of the points in each group. The colours, points, labels, title and background will be altered and the legend removed. A panel of dot plots like Plot 1B will be generated.

  1. Add a line through the median of the points in each group.
  2. Colour the groups choosing any colours you like.
  3. Make the points bigger.
  4. Change the x and y axis labels.
  5. Add a title.
  6. Remove the legend.
  7. Format the background.

Plot 2 - Advanced

In addition to the steps above, calculations will be performed on the data to generate normalised counts. A panel of dot plots like Plot 2 will be generated.

  1. Calculate the normalised counts per bead for each cell type. Total number of beads is 3000.
  2. Calculate the normalised counts per gram tumour for each cell type. Control and Drug 1 tumour weights were 0.1g, Drug 2 was 0.2g.
  3. Format the data to plot with ggplot.
  4. Create one plot for each cell type like plot 2.

Optional
Add any other customisations you like or create a different plot type for the data.

Getting started

  • To get started either
    • Download and install R and RStudio onto your computer if you dont already have them. Install tidyverse package. Download Excel file from link in Data section above.
    • Or use an Rstudio Cloud project that has everything set up. Click on this RStudio project link (create a free RStudio Cloud account if you dont have one). Note: When the project opens, click top menu Save a Permanent Copy if you want any edits you make to be saved.
